{
  "text": "The innovations to decrease BPD are new ways to give surfactant and more effective methods to deliver CPAP or noninvasive ventilation. Aerosolization of surfactant is an old idea that is again being evaluated [CITATION_1] . Synchronized nasal ventilation avoids the endotracheal tube and can support infants with apnea [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Neural adjusted ventilatory assist (NAVA) is a technique for timing and modulating mechanical ventilation cycles using the electrical signal from the diaphragm detected with a fine catheter in the distal esophagus. NAVA is being evaluated for noninvasive ventilation of infants [CITATION_4] . Diblasi et al. [CITATION_5] recently reported that a change in configuration of the pressure controller for bubble CPAP can strikingly increase the ability of bubble CPAP to assist ventilation in animal models. A package of individualized interventions to support ventilation, minimize oxygen exposure, minimize apnea, and encourage growth should decrease both the frequency and severity of BPD, but this disease will not go away.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "10990386",
    "[CITATION_2]": "29513466",
